Gas bladder abbreviated cordiform (wider than long), simple (without diverticula) and with a well-developed internal T-shaped septum (
Fig. 2a
).

Remarks. According to Kullander (1995) at least ten nominal fish species are known from the upper rio Aripuanã, suggesting a high degree of endemism for this portion of the river. Noteworthy is the presence of two carnivorous species above the rio Aripuanã waterfalls, the “sapatão” or “ mandubé” (
Trachycorystes menezesi
) and the “traíra” (
Hoplias malabaricus
), both of which are remarkably abundant. Both species were easily captured in large numbers in the rio Aripuanã using fishhooks during the expedition. The section of the river below the falls is dominated by the much diversified Amazonian carnivorous fishes that reach the base of the falls, but are almost completely absent in the section above the falls (H. A. Britski, pers. obs.). The large number of individuals in populations of
T . menezesi
(as well as of
H . malabaricus
) may be attributed to the absence of competitors above the falls of Dardanelos and Andorinhas.
